How then should it flow from snow, when it flows from the hottest parts to those which are cooler? And indeed most of the facts are such as to convince a man (one at least who is capable of reasoning about such matters), that it is not at all likely that it flows from snow. The first and greatest evidence is afforded by the winds, which blow â hot from these regionsÍ¾ the second is that the land is rain- less always and without frost, whereas after snow has fallen rain must necessarily come within five days, so that if it snowed in those parts rain would fall thereÍ¾ the third evidence is afforded by the people dwelling there, who are of a black colour by reason of the burning heat. More- over kites and swallows remain there through the year and do not leave the landÍ¾ and cranes flying from the cold weather which comes on in the region of Scythia come regularly to these parts for wintering: if then it snowed ever so little in that land through which the Nile fiows and in which it has its rise, none of these things would take place, as necessity compels us to admit. If one would set forth the matter in the shortest way, all has now been saidÍ¾ for whatever region this god approaches most and stands directly above, this it may reasonably be supposed is most in want of water, and its native streams of rivers are dried up most.
